{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478763"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:15:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:15:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18809"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18809"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.7,0.05,0.06,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11542"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79410"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11542"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18809"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64732"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"5901"},{"type":"tags","id":"5943"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27164"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79410"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of progressive leg weakness and difficulty walking. Two weeks ago, he had a gastrointestinal illness with diarrhoea that resolved spontaneously. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 105/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has symmetric weakness of both legs (power 3/5) with absent deep tendon reflexes. Upper limb power is 4/5 with reduced reflexes. Sensation is intact. Cranial nerve examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECerebrospinal fluid analysis reveals protein 0.8 g/L (0.15-0.45) with normal cell count.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous methylprednisolone","Intravenous immunoglobulin","Oral prednisolone","Plasmapheresis","Supportive care only"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome (GBS): progressive symmetric weakness, areflexia, and antecedent gastrointestinal illness. The cerebrospinal fluid shows albuminocytologic dissociation (elevated protein with normal cell count), which is characteristic of GBS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous immunoglobulin\u003C/strong\u003E (IVIG) is the first-line treatment for moderate to severe GBS in children. It should be initiated early in the disease course to prevent progression and improve outcomes. The standard dose is 2g/kg, which can be given over 2-5 days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlasmapheresis\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative to IVIG and has similar efficacy. However, it is technically more challenging in children and requires specialized equipment and expertise. It is typically reserved for cases where IVIG is contraindicated or unavailable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupportive care only\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient given this patient\u0027s progressive weakness. While mild cases may improve with supportive care alone, this patient\u0027s symptoms warrant active treatment to prevent further deterioration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous methylprednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E are not recommended for GBS. Corticosteroids have not been shown to improve outcomes and may actually worsen the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClose monitoring of respiratory function is essential as approximately 15-20% of children with GBS develop respiratory failure requiring mechanical ventilation. Regular assessments of vital capacity, oxygen saturation, and signs of respiratory distress are crucial. Pain management and prevention of complications such as deep vein thrombosis are also important aspects of care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome typically presents with ascending symmetric weakness and areflexia.","Respiratory function monitoring is critical as respiratory failure can develop rapidly in Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome.","Intravenous immunoglobulin is first-line treatment for moderate to severe Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome in children."],"references":["Langille MM. Guillain-Barre Syndrome in Children and Adolescents. Adv Pediatr. 2023 Aug;70(1):91-103. doi: 10.1016/j.yapd.2023.04.001. Epub 2023 May 12. PMID: 37422300."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64732"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18809"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64732"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T12:21:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T12:23:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11542"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79410"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":nu